5":"1057–1105","Bef 1120":"vóór 1120","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1057":"1057","1155":"1155","1088":"1088","1197":"1197","1096":"1096","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Conches-en-Ouche, Département de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie":"Conches-en-Ouche, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1088–1155":"1088–1155","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1125–1169":"1125–1169","1127–1197":"1127–1197","1057–1105":"1057–1105","Bef 1120":"before 1120","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1057":"1057","1155":"1155","1088":"1088","1197":"1197","1096":"1096","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Conches-en-Ouche, Département de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie":"Conches-en-Ouche, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Malet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: nickname from a diminutive of   Mal   ‘bad’ or from a derivative of the related Old French word <i>maleit</i> ‘accursed’ (see   Mallet   1). Compare   Malette  .","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Malo   (compare   Mallet   2).","French: variant of   Mallet   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Mal","meanings":["Slovenian: nickname for a physically small man, from <i>mal</i> ‘small, little’.","French (mainly Nord): nickname from <i>mal</i> ‘bad’ (from Latin <i>malus</i>).","Indian (northern states): variant of   Mall  ."]},{"name":"Malette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Alphonse, Francois, Jacques, Rejean, Serge.","French: variant or feminine form of   Malet   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this, reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":8,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":18,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Malet was born in 1088, in Conches-en-Ouche, Eure, Upper Normandy, France as the son of Gilbert Isaac Malet. He married Hesilia Crispin before 1120, in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1155, in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England, at the age of 67, and was buried in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England."},"et":{"1088–1155":"1088–1155","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1125–1169":"1125–1169","1127–1197":"1127–1197","1057–1105":"1057–1105","Bef 1120":"enne 1120","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1057":"1057","1155":"1155","1088":"1088","1197":"1197","1096":"1096","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Conches-en-Ouche, Département de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie":"Conches-en-Ouche, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1088–1155":"1088–1155","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1125–1169":"1125–1169","1127–1197":"1127–1197","1057–1105":"1057–1105","Bef 1120":"ennen vuotta 1120","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1057":"1057","1155":"1155","1088":"1088","1197":"1197","1096":"1096","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Conches-en-Ouche, Département de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie":"Conches-en-Ouche, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1088–1155":"1088–11